text: I heard Take it easy this past winter.  The first of this Lady's  music I'd Heard.  She writes, She is a very talented Pianist, But Her Voice!!!. Finally your voice cracks at 12 - 14 & you are fired.   But Adelle!!!?? the aforementioned song...Virtuoso Piano But on top of everything - her voice.  Very strong and she is 100% in charge of wherever it goes.  The first Day I heard her I must have played that song 20 - 30 times. Literally mesmerized by her talent as a vocalist...all day.  I called my cousin/sister about her and she said yup, that's her.  She is a trained Classical Pianist and she Praised her playing.  For me, the talent that kicks me in the head is her vocal skill/style.  Breathing easy, phrasing, perfect, melding her Falsetto with her Diaphragm , Just pure, easy, natural skill. At 6:26, a homage to the tragically beautiful painting, "Ophelia" by John Everett Millais. His muse "Ophelia" from William Shakespeare's "Hamlet".

"The episode depicted is not usually seen onstage, as in Shakespeare's text it exists only in Gertrude's description. Out of her mind with grief, Ophelia has been making garlands of wildflowers. She climbs into a willow tree overhanging a brook to dangle some from its branches, and a bough breaks beneath her. She lies in the water singing songs, as if unaware of her danger ("incapable of her own distress"). Her clothes, trapping air, have allowed her to temporarily stay afloat ("Her clothes spread wide, / And, mermaid-like, awhile they bore her up."). But eventually, "her garments, heavy with their drink, / Pull'd the poor wretch from her melodious lay" down "to muddy death"..." (Wikipedia, 2023)

text:
Wow! After hearing this song, I felt the need to write just something. Coming from the perspective of a middle aged man suffering from Asperger’s, this sums up the last 15yrs of my life. From a young age, where diagnosis wasn’t available, you were just the naughty kid, the kid that got scalded all the time, the kid that was never understood, never fully accepted but yet somehow got through by being someone that wasn’t really me. In my older years it cost me a marriage, leaving two beautiful children, although they stayed true to me, there was always me, being that person I wasn’t that seemed to make it so, in someways me being false. A second marriage and two stepchildren and another daughter, very much feeling blessed, it became apparent that my youngest had some issues, a trait I recognised. My daughter had tests, meetings through years of being excluded by friends and family, through no fault of her own, heartbreaking as a parent and devastating for a child, my daughter. Years later I decided to get myself tested and low and behold, the diagnosis was high function Asperger’s syndrome, this opened up a world of learning, trying to reinvent yourself, which is still going on to this day with many many counselling sessions. My daughter thankfully have received a lot of help, support and guidance, something that is much harder for a man approaching his 60th birthday next year. All in all, if I could have written, in words, how I’ve felt years now, these would have been those words. The one person, the only person who has stood by my daughter and I, is my wife and I truly, truly thank her and I do, ever day, just for understanding, forgiving our moments of madness.
